N165dO3fu37cf3nn77bf/JQI83dxcMVhcdW11XV19XkEhoaM1OTn5av61psZG4vBQaUV5WVkJXFWVFeWVFZlZFxEBu/cYGxkBAxiB0sEDB42MjA7s27d9%2bzZgaWmJ2NzY2NjW1ubgwQM7d%2bx45513Dh403LljOyiE90EV7Nf2be/AP2Vjd%2bir339o0HfqmD2Y2M3dzd3jvwV3ZxcUCqzj7uHiCkb0gFuMHzYgKMjdwxMFK%2b7uLq6uMD9tb48UkLf%2bfffevZZWNhB1g//u9cZCf/79RwbD5064%2bngFot2xXh7/P/B/Day3J8bDzdfd1R/9eh3tjvNBuzmc37vt7f07thnu2Wm8b4/hru17t7%2b97zXgke72HR30E2RFv46M%2bon%2b/R3bIJFPHjny6d21/wUw8YKa3yRxxgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==' /%3e%3c/svg%3e\" width=\"1006\" alt=\"Our first Kotlin Firefox extension in effect\" data-srcset=\"/assets/static/kotlin-first-extension.82a2fbd.e3e9f2c9d10a081785dadc40786585a3.png 480w, /assets/static/kotlin-first-extension.5c5033d.e3e9f2c9d10a081785dadc40786585a3.png 1006w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 1006px) 100vw, 1006px\" data-src=\"/assets/static/kotlin-first-extension.5c5033d.e3e9f2c9d10a081785dadc40786585a3.png\"><noscript><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loaded\" src=\"/assets/static/kotlin-first-extension.5c5033d.e3e9f2c9d10a081785dadc40786585a3.png\" width=\"1006\" alt=\"Our first Kotlin Firefox extension in effect\"></noscript></p>\n<p>Now, let’s change the color of the border from red to green. To do so, we modify our code to</p>\n<pre class=\"language-kotlin\"><code class=\"language-kotlin\">document<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>body<span class=\"token operator\">?</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>style<span class=\"token operator\">?</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>border <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"5px solid green\"</span></code></pre>\n<p>When we switch back to Firefox, we see (after a short delay) that our changes are automatically applied without us having to run any commands.</p>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\"><a href=\"#conclusion\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"hashtag\"></span></a>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>In this post we saw how to write a simple Firefox extension in Kotlin JS that injects a content script. The setup was fairly easy and we didn’t hit any major roadblocks. Additionally, the workflow including continuous building and live reloading the extension turned out to be pretty comfortable.</p>\n<p>In the follow-up post <a href=\"/blog/kotlin-second-webextension/\">Your Second Firefox extension in Kotlin</a> I’m diving deeper in the extension development process and show how to call Browser APIs.</p>\n","date":"18 November 2017","twitter":"https://twitter.com/Cypressious/status/931974273920651264","description":"Writing a Browser Extension in KotlinJS"}},"context":{}}